docs.abstract: Affordable homes can be hard to buy because lenders don’t make much money on small loans. But programs to encourage homeownership can help buyers build wealth.
docs.snippet: Affordable homes can be hard to buy because lenders don’t make much money on small loans. But programs to encourage homeownership can help buyers build wealth.
docs.lead_paragraph: The Shawnee neighborhood in Louisville, Ky., is a paradox: The houses are affordable, but they can be difficult to buy. The prices are so low that most banks and lenders will not bother writing mortgages for them.

headline.main: Where a Little Mortgage Goes a Long Way
headline.print_headline: Where a Little Mortgage Can Give a Big Boost

docs.abstract: “You don’t have to follow the norms,” says this artist who makes wrenching sculptures transformed by gunfire and radically altered heirloom quilts. A studio visit sheds light on his personal journey.
docs.snippet: “You don’t have to follow the norms,” says this artist who makes wrenching sculptures transformed by gunfire and radically altered heirloom quilts. A studio visit sheds light on his personal journey.
docs.lead_paragraph: One afternoon in June, the artist Sanford Biggers, having returned to the city after a stretch bunkered out of town with his wife and young daughter to avoid the pandemic, opened up his expansive basement studio in Harlem for a socially-distanced visit.

docs.abstract: In the fall ad campaigns, race-conscious casting now matters. Is it progress, or is it cynicism?
docs.snippet: In the fall ad campaigns, race-conscious casting now matters. Is it progress, or is it cynicism?
docs.lead_paragraph: Nearly a decade ago, when Precious Lee arrived for a modeling go-see, she was grilled about her ethnic background. The clients, who were representing a deep-pocketed luxury brand, were looking for a mixed-race model, Ms. Lee recalled. When she told them that she was Black, their faces fell.

docs.abstract: Osaka won her semifinal match on Friday, walking to the court with a T-shirt bearing the Black Lives Matter slogan.
docs.snippet: Osaka won her semifinal match on Friday, walking to the court with a T-shirt bearing the Black Lives Matter slogan.
docs.lead_paragraph: Two days after leading her sport into a social justice work stoppage, Naomi Osaka won her semifinal match on Friday in the Western & Southern Open, a match she was willing to forfeit to spark a broader conversation in the tennis world about racism.

headline.main: Naomi Osaka Returns After Protest Prompts Tournament’s Pause
headline.print_headline: She Led a Walkout for Racial Justice. And Then She Made the Final.

docs.abstract: “People protest in many different ways,” a young activist in the Bay Area says. For her and others in her performance group, one way is dance.

docs.lead_paragraph: When racial justice protests were sweeping the country in June, Shayla Avery, 16, chose her school in Berkeley, Calif., as the site of her first demonstration.

headline.main: Making a Connection Between Movement and Social Movements

docs.abstract: A new study shows that 11 percent of top aides shaping policy and public messaging in senators’ Washington offices are people of color, compared with almost 40 percent of the American populace.
docs.snippet: A new study shows that 11 percent of top aides shaping policy and public messaging in senators’ Washington offices are people of color, compared with almost 40 percent of the American populace.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — As senators chart a response to a deadly pandemic and an economic crisis that have disproportionately hurt Black Americans and other people of color, the top aides leading their offices are overwhelmingly white — far more so than the country as a whole.

headline.main: Senators Lead an Increasingly Diverse Nation. Their Top Aides Are Mostly White.
headline.print_headline: Top Aides of Senators Often Do Not Resemble Constituents Back Home

docs.abstract: The deafening silence of not having sports provided a powerful message from athletes demanding racial justice, after kneeling and slogans on jerseys seemed to have lost potency.
docs.snippet: The deafening silence of not having sports provided a powerful message from athletes demanding racial justice, after kneeling and slogans on jerseys seemed to have lost potency.
docs.lead_paragraph: It was the silence that spoke loudest.

headline.main: With Walkouts, a New High Bar for Protests in Sports Is Set
headline.print_headline: For a Time, The Sound Of Sports Is Silence

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Deploying a little-known National Guard reconnaissance plane in four American cities to monitor protests this spring did not violate rules against the military collecting intelligence on citizens, a Pentagon report has concluded.
